\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a set with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|=10$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the equivalence classes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that we have elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in A$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[a\right]\right|=3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[b\right]\right|=5$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[c\right]\right|=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Are any of 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 related by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

?.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
No, according to theorem 22.1 in the book, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]=\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in A$
\end_inset

.
 And if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]=\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

 then they must have the same cardinality.
 Since the cardinality of the equivalence classes of 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are different, they cannot be the same equivalence class, and hence not
 related.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How many equivalence classes for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 are there in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Since the cardinality of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

, the sum of the cardinality of the elements of its partition by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 must equal 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

.
 That is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[a\right]\right|+\left|\left[b\right]\right|+\left|\left[c\right]\right|+\cdots=10$
\end_inset

.
 Since, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[a\right]\right|+\left|\left[b\right]\right|+\left|\left[c\right]\right|=9$
\end_inset

 there can only be one other equivalence class of the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 whose cardinality is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)\sim\left(c,d\right)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}+d^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We saw in Example 21.6 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left(3,4\right)\right]$
\end_inset

, both as a set and geometrically.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left(3,4\right)\right]=\left\{ \left(a,b\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\,:\,a^{2}+b^{2}=28\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 It is the set of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 that are a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{28}$
\end_inset

 from the origin.
 In other words, this set forms a circle around the origin with a radius
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{28}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For an arbitrary element 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, describe 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left(a,b\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left(a,b\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 is the set of points in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 that are a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}}$
\end_inset

 from the origin.
 (I think this is what the question is asking)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\infty\right)\times\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
In order to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\left[0,\infty\right)\times\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, we need to show that every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is related to at least one element 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and we need to show that every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is related to at most one element of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 I will separate this into show existence and uniqueness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Existence:
\series default
 Suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)\sim\left(a^{2}+b^{2},0\right)\in T$
\end_inset

.
 Hence there exists at least one element of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 that is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Uniqueness:
\series default
 Suppose by contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}\sim\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}\sim\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}\neq t_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}=\left(a^{2}+b^{2},0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}=\left(a^{2}+b^{2},0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}=t_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is related to only one element of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a traversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be the set of all the words in the English language.
 Define a relation of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\approx\beta$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 have the same first letter.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Reflexive
\series default
: Suppose directly 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 starts with some letter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, which is the same letter that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 starts with since its the same word.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a\approx a$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is reflexive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Symmetric
\series default
: Suppose directly 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\approx b$
\end_inset

.
 Then the first letter of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the same as the first letter of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Well, if they have the same first letter, then the first letter of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the first letter of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a\approx b$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Transitive
\series default
: Suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\approx b\land b\approx c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 start with the same letter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 start with the same letter.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 must start with the same letter, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\approx b$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is transitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive, it is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\alpha\right]$
\end_inset

 be the equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in W$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\text{"cat"}$
\end_inset

, list six elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\alpha\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
call, calling, calls, caller, car, cars
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How may equivalence classes are there in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Since there are 26 letters in the English alphabet, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $26$
\end_inset

 equivalence classes.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe a transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 would contain for every letter of the alphabet one word that starts with
 a letter of the alphabet.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a set with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements.
 Define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim A$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|X\right|=\left|Y\right|$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Reflexive
\series default
: Suppose directly 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|=x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Z}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|=x=\left|a\right|$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|R\left|a\right|$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Symmetric
\series default
: Suppose directly 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right|=x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Z}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right|=\left|a\right|$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right|R\left|a\right|$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Transitive
\series default
: Suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\sim b\land b\sim c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 hen 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|=x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|b\right|=x$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|c\right|=x$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{Z}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|=\left|c\right|$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|a\right|R\left|c\right|$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive, it is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe the equivalence classes for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The equivalence classes for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

, contains the subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 with the same cardinality.
 Hence, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 equivalence classes, since one equivalence class contains just the empty
 set.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How many equivalence classes are there for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
As stated earlier, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 equivalence classes, since one equivalence class contains just the empty
 set.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Describe a transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 would contain one element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 for every distinct cardinality.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How many elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 are in each equivalence class?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m\right]$
\end_inset

 denote the equivalence class for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 that contains all the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 with cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, them 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[m\right]\right|=\left(\begin{matrix}n\\
m
\end{matrix}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,10\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in A$
\end_inset

, define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i}=\left\{ X\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)\,:\,i\,\text{is the least element of X}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\left\{ \left\{ \emptyset\right\} ,S_{1},\ldots,S_{10}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
To show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P\left(A\right)},$
\end_inset

 we need to show that no set in 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is empty, every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is a member of some element of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, and that any two distinct elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are disjoint.
 We will prove each property separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
(Nonempty pieces)
\series default
: We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i}=\left\{ X\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)\,:\,i\,\text{is the least element of X}\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 contains all of the possible subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1\right\} ,\left\{ 2\right\} ,\ldots,\left\{ 10\right\} $
\end_inset

 must be elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, and thus the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ i\right\} $
\end_inset

 must be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in A$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that none of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 are empty, and since the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset\right\} $
\end_inset

 is clearly not empty, none of the sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are empty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
(Covering)
\series default
: We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i}=\left\{ X\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)\,:\,i\,\text{is the least element of X}\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

since each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 has a least element 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in A$
\end_inset

 except for the empty set, then each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, except for the empty set, must be an element of one of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 And since an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 contains the empty set, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
(Disjoint Pieces)
\series default
: We suppose by contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k},S_{m}\in P$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $k,m\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq m$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}\cap S_{m}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}=\left\{ X\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)\,:\,k\,\text{is the least element of X}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}=\left\{ X\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)\,:\,m\,\text{is the least element of X}\right\} $
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}$
\end_inset

 must have an element 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\in\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 in common.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 cannot contain two different least elements, the only way for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\in S_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\in S_{m}$
\end_inset

 would be for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}=S_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 But this is a contradiction.
 Thus, every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is disjoint.
 We quickly state that the element 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \emptyset\right\} $
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is disjoint from all other sets since 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\not\in A$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\not\in S_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We have shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 contains no empty pieces, is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

, and that its pieces are disjoint.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a covering of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be the equivalence relation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 How many equivalence classes does 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 have?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 contains 11 disjoint elements, then there are 11 equivalence classes according
 to Theorem 22.9.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Write down a transversal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $T=\left\{ \emptyset,\left\{ 1\right\} ,\left\{ 2\right\} ,\left\{ 3\right\} ,\left\{ 4\right\} ,\left\{ 5\right\} ,\left\{ 6\right\} ,\left\{ 7\right\} ,\left\{ 8\right\} ,\left\{ 9\right\} ,\left\{ 10\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Determine the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left\{ 8,9,10\right\} \right]$
\end_inset

 by listing its elements.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left\{ 8,9,10\right\} \right]=\left\{ \left\{ 8\right\} ,\left\{ 8,9\right\} ,\left\{ 8,10\right\} ,\left\{ 8,9,10\right\} \right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How large is the equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left\{ 2,3,4\right\} \right]$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Its huge! 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left[\left\{ 2,3,4\right\} \right]\right|=1+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
1
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
2
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
3
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
4
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
5
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
6
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
7
\end{matrix}\right)+\left(\begin{matrix}8\\
8
\end{matrix}\right)=256.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise
Give another proof of Theorem 22.1, by proving that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that your proof should not use any theorems after or including Theorem
 22.1; it should only use basic properties of equivalence relations and equivalen
ce classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We prove the equivalence by proving three implications: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\right)\implies\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)\implies\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)\implies\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\right)\implies\left(2\right):$
\end_inset

 We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 Since an equivalence relation is reflexive we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Since it is symmetric, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim x$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the intersection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]\cap\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

 must contain at least the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 and therefore cannot be empty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)\implies\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

: Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]\cap\left[y\right]\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 We wish to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]=\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 We will prove this equality by showing both inclusions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We first show 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]\subseteq\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim z$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]\cap\left[y\right]\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 there is an element 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 that is in both 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim m$
\end_inset

.
 Using the symmetric property and transitive properties of equivalence relations
 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $z\sim m$
\end_inset

.
 Using the same properties again we get 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim z$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We now show 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[y\right]\subseteq\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This is similar to the proof of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]\subseteq\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)\implies\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x\right]=\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This meas that 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\left[x\right]$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since all three implications hold, the theorem 22.1 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
It is claimed above that every equivalence relation corresponds uniquely
 to a partition.
 Prove the final piece of that claim, by showing the following: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 be two equivalence relations.
 Show that if their equivalence classes are the same, then the relations
 are the same.
 (In other words, conclude that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\approx b$
\end_inset

.) For ease of notation, we will write the equivalence classes for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a\right]$
\end_inset

, and the equivalence classes for 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that the equivalence relations 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 have the same equivalence classes, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a\right]=\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Using the definition of equivalence classes, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[a\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,x\right)\in\sim$
\end_inset

, and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,x\right)\in\approx$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a\right]=\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 must have the same elements as 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

.
 Thus they are equal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Integers modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We wish to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 This is a biconditional statement, so we will show both implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\implies\right):$
\end_inset

 We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bar{a}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv0\,\left(\mod\:n\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In other words 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a-0$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\impliedby\right):$
\end_inset

 We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a$
\end_inset

.
 This can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid\left(a-0\right)$
\end_inset

, which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv0\,\left(\mod\:n\right)$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bar{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since both implications hold, the statement that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Compute the following.
 Write the results as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 non-negative and as small as possible.
 For this problem let 
\begin_inset Formula $\%$
\end_inset

 denote modulus 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{6}+\bar{7}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{9}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(6+7\right)\%9=4$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{6}\cdot\bar{7}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{9}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(6\cdot7\right)\%9=6$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{6}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{59}\cdot\overline{119}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{30}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(59\cdot119\right)\%30=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{6}\cdot\bar{5}+\overline{85}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{7}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(6\cdot5+85\right)\%7=3$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{2}^{10}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{5}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2^{10}\right)\%5=\left(2^{4}\cdot2^{4}\cdot2^{2}\right)\%5=4$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{4}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
