\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

The table shows that there is not 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{2}\cdot Y=\bar{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
In this exercise we generalize what was done in the previous two exercises.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is composite, prove that there are elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a},\bar{b}\in\mathbb{Z}_{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

 even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a},\bar{b}\neq\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is composite.
 Then, according to theorem 19.3, there exists two integers 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1<x,y<n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cdot y=n$
\end_inset

.
 The integers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are elements of their respective equivalence classes 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=\left\{ x+kn\,:k\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}=\left\{ y+\ell n\,:\ell\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying them together yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{x\cdot y} & =\left\{ \left(x+kn\right)\left(y+\ell n\right)\,:\,k,\ell\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} \\
 & =\left\{ xy+ykn+x\ell n+kn\ell n\,:\,k,\ell\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} \\
 & =\left\{ n+ykn+x\ell n+kn\ell n\,:\,k,\ell\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} \\
 & =\left\{ 0+mn\,:\,m\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} \\
 & =\bar{0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is prime, prove that given 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a},\bar{b}\in\mathbb{Z}_{n}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We assume directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is prime and that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a},\bar{b}\in\mathbb{Z}_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The equivalence classes 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}=\left\{ a+kn\,:\,k\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}=\left\{ b+\ell n\,:\,\ell\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying them together we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b} & =\left\{ \left(a+kn\right)\left(b+\ell n\right)\,:\,m,k\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} \\
 & =\left\{ \left(ab+a\ell n+bkn+kn\ell n\right),\,:\,m,k\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} .
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(ab+a\ell n+bkn+kn\ell n\right)=mn$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 This would require that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid ab$
\end_inset

.
 According to Euclid's lemma, since 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid ab$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is prime, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid a$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid b$
\end_inset

.
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $a=ng$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b=nh$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}=\left\{ gn+kn\,:\,k,g\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}=\left\{ hn+\ell n\,:\,\ell,g\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is prime, prove that for any nonzero 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\in\mathbb{Z}_{n}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{b}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}=\bar{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
We suppose directly that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is prime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\in\mathbb{Z}_{n}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\neq\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}=\left\{ a+kn\,:\,k\in\mathbb{Z}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{GCD}\left(a,n\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to write 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $1=ax+ny$
\end_inset

 .
 This can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(-y\right)=ax-1$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $n\mid ax-1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,n$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bar{b}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b+pn$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\equiv b\,\text{mod}\,n$
\end_inset

..
 Thus we can substitute in 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\equiv1\,\text{mod}\,n$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}\cdot\bar{b}=\bar{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

